# batch_loop.py
this will be the primitive version of the conversational AI. It will be much
slower because we will have to wait for user to finisih speaking, and then
process the audio, then send it baack to user in one batch_loop

#stream_loop.py
we will use a more advanced architecrure here. We will use web sockets
to stream 

User speaks → audio is streamed as small chunks (e.g., 20–100ms frames).

STT streaming: those chunks go to Deepgram over WebSockets.

You receive partial transcripts continuously.

You also receive final transcripts once Deepgram is confident the utterance is complete.

Turn detection (endpointing): you decide when the user is “done” (silence, STT final, confidence rules).

LLM: when an utterance is final, you send it to the LLM with the ongoing state.

Optionally call tools (calendar lookup, FAQs, etc.).

TTS streaming or chunked:

You send the response text to ElevenLabs.

Ideally you request streaming audio output (or fetch audio quickly and start playing as soon as bytes arrive).

Stream back to the user:

Web app: stream to the browser audio element / WebAudio.

Phone cal

how webRTC works analogy:
Step 1 — POST /api/offer (You say "can we talk?")
Your browser sends a message to the server saying "here's what I can do — my microphone format, my connection info, etc." This is called an SDP offer.
The server responds with "great, here's what I can do too" — that's the SDP answer. At this point both sides have agreed on HOW they'll talk, but the connection isn't open yet.

Step 2 — PATCH /api/offer (You exchange addresses)
Now both sides need to find the best route to actually reach each other on the network. They swap ICE candidates — basically a list of possible "addresses" to try.
Think of it like texting someone "try reaching me at home, or my cell, or my work phone" — the two sides try each option until one works.